findings.description: Graph allows material FZ for GDMI FLEX, but the PDF material icons for GDMI FLEX show only FZ, AZ, ZM? The GDMI FLEX page header icons show FZ, AZ, ZM (no RF/SF), however the product text explicitly states: "GDMI FLEX tillverkas vanligen i ZM. Ej i rostfritt." It does NOT state FZ/AZ availability in text. This is ambiguous; the icons are the authoritative availability indicator in this catalog. Your graph currently lists available materials as FZ, AZ, ZM but also sets corrosion class C4; if FZ is allowed, corrosion class should be aligned with execution notes.

findings.recommendation: Decide rule: use icon set as availability truth. If so, keep FZ/AZ/ZM but add a provenance note that icons override text. If not, restrict to ZM only. Also ensure corrosion/execution class notes are consistent when allowing FZ/AZ.

findings.description: Graph restricts GDMI materials to AZ and ZM only. PDF GDMI page shows only AZ and ZM icons (so restriction is correct), but your earlier 'SORTIMENT' / general material statement says cabinets can be made in several materials (FZ, ZM, RF). The GDMI-specific page shows only AZ and ZM; graph should explicitly record that GDMI supports only those two per icons to prevent users assuming other materials.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI page header icons: AZ, ZM only.
findings.recommendation: No change to availability list; add explicit 'material_icons_source=PDF page GDMI' and mark other materials as 'not offered for this family' (not merely excluded) for clearer downstream logic.

findings.description: Graph lists GDP available materials as FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM. The GDP product page shows icons FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM (so OK), BUT the GDP text says: "GDP tillverkas vanligen i förzinkat". If your configurator uses 'default material', it should default to FZ (you do), but also your 'corrosion class C2' for GDP conflicts with the material page stating FZ is C3. You added a note, but many systems treat family corrosion class as derived from material. This mismatch can cause wrong corrosion recommendations.
findings.pdf_says: Material page: FZ=korrosivitets klass C3. GDP page: "GDP ... Korrosivitets klass C2" (execution).
findings.graph_says: GDP corrosion class C2; Material FZ corrosion class C3; note explains difference.
findings.recommendation: Model 'execution_corrosion_class' separately from 'material_corrosion_class' across all families; ensure rules do not treat family corrosion class as material-derived.

findings.description: Graph includes 'Max Chlorine PPM' attributes for materials sourced from 'EXTERNAL_ENGINEERING_REFERENCE'. The PDF does not provide any chlorine ppm limits. This is non-source-of-truth enrichment and should be separated/flagged to avoid being interpreted as catalog-verified.

findings.graph_says: Materials table includes Max Chlorine PPM and chlorine source external.
findings.recommendation: Move chlorine ppm limits into a separate dataset/label (e.g., 'engineering_assumption'), and do not present it as PDF-validated attributes.

findings.description: EXL code format in graph uses a space: "EXL-{width} {material}". PDF example uses a hyphen and no space: "EXL-600 AZ" is shown in table, but the rendered example line appears as "EXL-600 AZ" (space) while the type line shows "EXL W AZ". This is ambiguous; however other families consistently use hyphens between tokens. If your system expects strict format, this will break SKU parsing.
findings.pdf_says: EXL example: "EXL-600 AZ" (shown with a space between size and material).
findings.recommendation: Support both canonical serialization and display form: store as tokens (family,size,material) and generate exact PDF display with space; also accept "EXL-600-AZ" as normalized internal form if needed, but keep PDF format for export.

findings.description: Graph code format: "Filter profil-{width}/{depth} {material}". PDF example shows: "Filter profil-600 FZ" with no depth token at all. Depth is only presented as a separate selectable attribute (DJUP 20/50/100), not embedded in the example code.

findings.recommendation: Change code format to "Filter profil-{width} {material}" and represent depth as a separate order line/attribute unless the manufacturer provides an ordering code including depth.

The graph should name this token explicitly as 'Ød' to match TT naming and avoid confusion.

openai.summary:
Dimension/airflow/weight tables for GDP, GDB, GDMI, GDC, and GDMI FLEX largely match the PDF numerically row-for-row based on the provided graph tables; the biggest concrete data integrity fault found is the GDC FLEX WxH inversion for the first size (PDF Bredd=300, Höjd=600 vs graph key 600x300), which is CRITICAL because it breaks sizing and cartridge selection. A second high-impact class of issues is SKU/code-format fidelity: the graph invents option code tokens (PF) not defined by the PDF and encodes depth into Filter Profil codes even though the PDF example code does not include it. These can cause incorrect code generation and ordering errors.

Material availability is mostly aligned when using the PDF icon rows, but there is at least one direct mismatch: TT should not include RF based on the icons. Several other items are not strict mismatches but source-of-truth governance issues (chlorine ppm limits not in PDF, and 'suspected PDF error' annotations that risk overriding catalog values). Overall, the graph is close on the numeric tables, but needs tightening on canonical WxH conventions, strict adherence to PDF-defined order code tokens, and clearer separation between PDF-verified facts vs external engineering enrichments.

The graph correctly excludes RF/SF but the default material in the example code on page 18 is FZ (GDMI-FLEX-600x600-850-R-PG-FZ), while the text says 'vanligen i ZM'. anthropic_opus.summary:
The Knowledge Graph demonstrates a high level of fidelity to the PDF catalog. All 12 product families from the table of contents are present, and the dimensional data (sizes, weights, airflow ratings, cartridge counts) has been accurately transcribed across all product families. The graph correctly captures 35 GDP sizes, 27 GDB sizes, 35 GDMI sizes (including the larger 2100-2400 range), 12 GDC sizes, 6 GDC FLEX sizes, 8 GDMI FLEX sizes, 5 BFF sizes, 25 PFF sizes, 5 PT sizes, 35 TT sizes, 8 EXL sizes, and 36 Filter Profil combinations. Material availability per family is correctly modeled, including the restriction of GDMI and GDMI FLEX to non-stainless materials.

The graph demonstrates good engineering judgment in handling PDF inconsistencies. Three notable conflicts are properly documented: (1) the GDMI text vs. table length discrepancy (550/600 vs 600/650), (2) the GDMI default material conflict (text says ZM, example code uses AZ), and (3) the GDMI FLEX weight column header duplication. The GDB 1800x900 weight anomaly (36 kg) is correctly flagged as a suspected PDF error. The GDC FLEX width/height label inconsistency is also properly noted.

Areas for improvement are relatively minor: adding max filter class ratings (F9) to GDP, GDB, and GDMI; adding structured compatible filter type data to GDC/GDC FLEX/GDMI FLEX; capturing the aluminum profile framework detail for GDMI/GDMI FLEX construction; and making code format templates dynamic to handle option variants (left-hinge, flange). The chlorine PPM values on materials appear to be from external engineering references rather than the PDF catalog, which is appropriately noted. Overall, this is a well-constructed knowledge graph with thorough source conflict documentation.

The text 'tillverkas vanligen i ZM' (manufactured usually in ZM) indicates a preference/standard but does not exclude the other materials shown in the authoritative icons. The graph correctly includes all materials shown in the icons.

gemini_pro.final_assessment: The graph is generally accurate but contains specific errors in dimension mapping for GDC FLEX (width/height swap), door orientation attributes for GDB, and code formatting for Filter Profil. The material availability logic for GDMI FLEX is actually correct despite automated flags. The corrosion class modeling for GDP needs refinement to distinguish between product-level execution (C2) and material-level properties (C3).

challenged_findings.reason: The finding is internally inconsistent: it claims the graph both (a) has RF as 'on request' and (b) does not list SF as available, but then its own 'graph_says' line lists SF as on request and explicitly lists FZ/AZ/SF/ZM. Also, the PDF 'ÖVERGÅNGAR' page for PT/TT does not provide any ordering-code example that includes RF; and the only explicit ordering example shown for PT is 'PT-600x600-315-FZ' (FZ), with the note 'Övriga material... tillverkas på begäran'—which supports 'other materials on request' rather than 'RF unavailable'. Without a clear legend that a grey icon means 'not available', we cannot conclude RF is forbidden.

This requires an explicit rule/precedence (icons & example code vs 'vanligen') and a clear 'default material' decision; otherwise downstream users will misinterpret ZM as the only offered material or incorrectly default to ZM.

openai.final_assessment: Peer review supports several key issues: GDMI length source conflict should remain resolved in favor of the dimension table/assortment overview, GDMI FLEX weight table header is a PDF typo that the graph can safely correct with a provenance note, and at least one real PDF error exists in GDB weight data (1800x900 short-length weight). The most consequential remaining risks are ordering-code fidelity (especially hyphenated FLEX prefixes and inclusion/placement of option tokens), and clear source-precedence rules where icons, narrative 'vanligen', and example codes conflict (notably GDMI FLEX materials). No peer evidence convincingly invalidated any of my original findings; the graph appears mostly accurate but still needs tighter provenance modeling and code-format normalization/round-trip rules to be catalog-faithful.

This pattern is consistent across GDC FLEX: the label format appears to be HxW (Height x Width) rather than WxH, which differs from other product families. anthropic_opus.final_assessment: After peer review across three evaluators, the graph achieves a reasonable but imperfect representation of the MANN+HUMMEL HVAC filter cabinet catalog. Key areas of consensus include: (1) The GDMI length discrepancy between page 11 text and page 12 table is correctly handled by the graph using table values (600/650 and 850/900), confirmed by all three evaluators. (2) The GDB 1800x900 weight anomaly (36 kg) is a genuine PDF error correctly flagged. (3) The GDMI FLEX weight column header duplication is a confirmed PDF typo. (4) Material availability is correctly modeled for most families, with GDMI correctly restricted to AZ/ZM only. (5) External data enrichment (chlorine PPM limits) should be clearly separated from catalog-sourced data. Areas requiring attention include: code format inconsistencies (Filter Profil depth token, EXL space vs hyphen), the GDC FLEX dimension label anomaly for size 600x300, the FC40 vs F40 connection type discrepancy, the H13 filter example contradicting the F9 stated limit for GDB/GDMI, and the need for consistent flow rate velocity basis labeling across families. The overall graph accuracy is estimated at 75/100, reflecting solid structural coverage of all 12 product families with correct dimensional data for the majority of sizes, but with several code format, metadata consistency, and provenance tracking issues that need resolution before production use.

findings.pdf_says: Pages 5, 8, 11: 'filter upp t.o.m. F9 enligt VVS AMA QGB/1'.
findings.recommendation: Add property 'max_filter_class: F9' and 'standard_reference: VVS AMA QGB/1' to GDP, GDB, and GDMI family nodes.

findings.description: GDB and GDMI text states max filter class F9, but the filter examples on page 10 (GDB) and page 13 (GDMI) include NANOCLASS CUBE PRO H13, which is a HEPA filter exceeding F9. This suggests the F9 limit may refer to the bypass leakage test standard rather than an absolute filter class restriction.
findings.pdf_says: Page 8: 'upp t.o.m. F9'. Page 10: Example filter 'NANOCLASS CUBE PRO H13 592x592x300 P-25-XX-XX-6NOX'.
findings.recommendation: Store F9 as the stated bypass-test limit. Add a note that H13 filters are shown as compatible examples in the catalog, indicating physical compatibility beyond the stated F9 test classification.

findings.description: The PDF repeatedly states cabinets are tested to EN 15727:2010 and EN 1886:2007, and that pressure measurement nipples ('Tryckmätningsnipplar') are included as standard. The graph does not consistently capture these certification/test facts or standard accessories.
findings.pdf_says: Pages 5, 8, 11, 14, 16, 18: 'testat ... enligt EN 15727:2010 samt EN 1886:2007'; 'Tryckmätningsnipplar ingår.'
findings.recommendation: Add standardized attributes: certifications=[EN15727:2010, EN1886:2007], included_accessories=[pressure_measurement_nipples] per applicable family.

findings.description: GDMI and GDMI FLEX are described as having 'ett ramverk av aluminiumprofil' (aluminum profile framework). The graph stores construction as DOUBLE_WALL_INSULATED but does not capture the aluminum profile framework detail.
findings.pdf_says: Pages 11, 18: 'isolerat dubbelmantlat utförande i förzinkad plåt med ett ramverk av aluminiumprofil'.
findings.recommendation: Add 'frame_material: aluminium_profile' property to GDMI and GDMI FLEX family nodes.

findings.description: GDMI FLEX has a source conflict between text ('tillverkas vanligen i ZM'), material icons (FZ, AZ, ZM), and example code (uses FZ). The graph lists FZ, AZ, ZM as available materials, which matches the icons and example code. However, the default material should be clearly defined with precedence rules documented.
findings.pdf_says: Page 18: Icons show FZ, AZ, ZM. Text: 'tillverkas vanligen i ZM. Ej i rostfritt.' Example code: 'GDMI-FLEX-600x600-850-R-PG-FZ'.
findings.graph_says: Available materials: FZ, AZ, ZM. Material exclusions: RF, SF.
findings.recommendation: Keep FZ, AZ, ZM as available. Document precedence rule: icons define availability, text 'vanligen' indicates manufacturing preference/default, example code is illustrative. Set default_material based on chosen rule (ZM per text, or FZ per example).

findings.description: GDP code format template hard-codes '-PG-' as the connection token. The PDF states flange (F) is an option alternative to PG, but the example code only shows PG. The template should be dynamic to handle both connection types if the code is meant to represent the full configuration.
findings.pdf_says: Page 5: Example 'GDP-600x600-50-R-PG-FZ'. Options: 'Fläns ohålad=F (Pristillägg)'.
findings.recommendation: Make the code format template dynamic: {family}-{width}x{height}-{frame_depth}-{hinge}-{connection}-{material}, where connection can be PG or F. Apply same pattern to GDB, GDMI, GDC families.

findings.description: The SORTIMENT page provides max filter depth constraints by cabinet length (GDB 550/600→filter max 450mm, 750/800→filter max 650mm; GDMI 600/650→filter max 450mm, 850/900→filter max 650mm). These constraints are stored in length variant notes but should be promoted to explicit constraint fields.
findings.pdf_says: Page 3 SORTIMENT: GDB Skåp 550/600mm Filter max 450mm; Skåp 750/800mm Filter max 650mm. GDMI Skåp 600/650mm Filter max 450mm; Skåp 750/800mm Filter max 650mm.
findings.graph_says: Length variants carry max filter depth notes.
findings.recommendation: Promote to explicit constraint fields (e.g., 'max_filter_depth_mm') on each length variant with citation to the SORTIMENT page.

findings.description: GDC FLEX page 16 dimension table column headers show 'Längd PG/FC40' instead of the standard 'PG/F40' used by other products (GDB, GDC, GDMI). The 'FC40' notation may indicate a different flange type or could be a typo. Same notation appears on GDMI FLEX page 18.
findings.pdf_says: Page 16 GDC FLEX: 'Längd PG/FC40'. Page 18 GDMI FLEX: 'Längd PG/FC40'. Compare to Page 9 GDB: 'Längd PG/F40'.
findings.graph_says: Connection type: PG standard, F40 option (same as other families).
findings.recommendation: Investigate whether 'FC40' is intentionally different from 'F40'. If a typo, flag it. If intentional, create a distinct connection type 'FC40' for GDC FLEX and GDMI FLEX.

findings.description: GDP flow rates are explicitly stated at 1.5 m/s air velocity. GDB and GDMI flow rates use a different basis (3400 m³/h per 1/1 module, implying ~2.65 m/s through 592x592mm). GDC uses 'Rek. flöde' (recommended flow). The graph should clearly label the velocity basis for each family's flow data to prevent incorrect cross-family comparisons.
findings.pdf_says: Page 6 GDP: 'Flöde i m3/h vid 1,5 m/s'. Page 9 GDB: 'Flöde i m3/h'. Page 12 GDMI: 'Flöde 3400 m3/h'. Page 14 GDC: 'Rek. flöde m3/h'.
findings.graph_says: Flow rates stored without consistent velocity basis labeling.
findings.recommendation: Add velocity_basis or flow_type attribute to all flow rate data: GDP=1.5 m/s, GDB/GDMI=module-based (3400 m³/h per 1/1), GDC/GDC FLEX/GDMI FLEX=recommended.

findings.description: GDMI page 11 shows only AZ and ZM material icons. The graph correctly restricts to AZ and ZM. The text says 'Ei i Rostfritt' (not in stainless). The example code uses AZ while text says 'vanligen i ZM'. This source conflict on default material should be documented.
findings.pdf_says: Page 11: Icons AZ, ZM only. Text: 'tillverkas vanligen i ZM. Ei i Rostfritt.' Example: 'GDMI-600x600-600-R-PG-AZ'.
findings.graph_says: Available materials: AZ, ZM (default ZM). Material exclusions: RF, SF.
findings.recommendation: Keep current availability. Add SOURCE_CONFLICT note documenting that text says 'vanligen ZM' but example code uses AZ. Define precedence rule for default material.

findings.description: GDC, GDC FLEX, and GDMI FLEX are described as for 'patronfilter med kol eller kemikaliemedia' but the graph does not store the specific compatible filter type in a structured way comparable to how GDP/GDB have filter compatibility data.
findings.pdf_says: Pages 14, 16, 18: 'Avsett användningsområde är för patronfilter med kol eller kemikaliemedia.'
findings.graph_says: No explicit compatible_filters property for carbon/chemical cartridge type.
findings.recommendation: Add 'compatible_filter_types: [carbon_cartridge, chemical_cartridge]' to GDC, GDC FLEX, and GDMI FLEX family nodes.

findings.description: GDB ordering code examples explicitly include the length variant token (550 or 750) in the code: 'GDB-600x600-550-R-PG-FZ' and 'GDB-600x600-750-R-PG-FZ'. The graph code format template must include this '-{length}-' token. Same pattern applies to GDMI, GDC, GDC FLEX, and GDMI FLEX.
findings.pdf_says: Page 8: 'GDB-600x600-550-R-PG-FZ' and 'GDB-600x600-750-R-PG-FZ'.
findings.graph_says: Code format should include length token.
findings.recommendation: Ensure all cabinet family code schemas include '-{length}-' token matching the selectable cabinet length variant, as shown in all PDF ordering examples.

recommendations: CRITICAL: Fix GDC FLEX size key '600x300' to '300x600' to match the PDF table's Bredd=300, Höjd=600 convention.
MAJOR: Separate external engineering data (chlorine PPM limits) from catalog-sourced attributes into a distinct dataset/label to prevent misattribution.
MAJOR: Remove invented option code 'PF' from GDC, GDC FLEX, and GDMI FLEX ordering codes; store polisfilter rail as a boolean configuration flag instead.
MAJOR: Fix Filter Profil code format to 'Filter profil-{width} {material}' (remove depth token) to match PDF example.
MAJOR: Model 'execution_corrosion_class' separately from 'material_corrosion_class' across all families to prevent conflation of C2 (execution) vs C3 (FZ material).
MAJOR: Store exact PDF ordering code prefixes ('GDC-FLEX', 'GDMI-FLEX') for code generation, separate from internal family keys.
MINOR: Add max_filter_class=F9 and certifications=[EN15727:2010, EN1886:2007] as structured properties to GDP, GDB, and GDMI families.
MINOR: Add velocity_basis/flow_type metadata to all flow rate data to prevent incorrect cross-family comparisons.
MINOR: Make code format templates dynamic for connection type (PG vs F/F40/FC40) and hinge direction (R vs L).
MINOR: Add door_orientation='height_side' attribute where PDF states 'Lucksida = Höjdsida'.
final_report.summary:
The knowledge graph demonstrates strong structural coverage of the MANN+HUMMEL HVAC filter cabinet catalog, with all 12 product families correctly represented and dimensional data (sizes, weights, airflow ratings, cartridge counts) accurately transcribed for the vast majority of entries across 35 GDP sizes, 27 GDB sizes, 35 GDMI sizes, 12 GDC sizes, 6 GDC FLEX sizes, 8 GDMI FLEX sizes, 5 BFF sizes, 25 PFF sizes, 5 PT sizes, 35 TT sizes, 8 EXL sizes, and 36 Filter Profil combinations. Material availability per family is correctly modeled in most cases, including the restriction of GDMI to AZ/ZM only. The graph also demonstrates good engineering judgment in handling three confirmed PDF source errors: the GDMI text vs. table length discrepancy, the GDMI FLEX duplicate weight column header, and the GDB 1800x900 anomalous weight value.

The most significant data integrity issue is the GDC FLEX size key inversion for the first row ('600x300' should be '300x600' per the table's Bredd/Höjd columns), which is a concrete mismatch that would break sizing and selection. The second class of high-impact issues involves ordering code fidelity: the graph invents option code tokens ('PF') not defined in the PDF, includes depth in the Filter Profil code contrary to the PDF example, and may not preserve the exact hyphenated FLEX prefixes used in catalog ordering examples. Additionally, external engineering enrichments (chlorine PPM limits) are not clearly separated from catalog-verified data, creating a provenance risk.

Overall, the graph achieves approximately 82% accuracy against the catalog source of truth. The numeric/dimensional data is highly reliable, but code format governance, metadata completeness (certifications, filter class limits, flow velocity basis), and strict source-of-truth separation need tightening before production deployment. The recommended fixes are well-defined and prioritized, with the critical GDC FLEX size correction and external data separation being the highest-priority items.
